      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_77d75a8b9751497483b0a3f8014e5993\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.reddit.com/r/buildapc/comments/1936ezw/whea_uncorrectable_error_temporarily_fix_when_i/\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ER...\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Hello everyone! I'm having issues with my Omen 15 laptop. I woke up in the morning and went to power my laptop and kept getting the WHEA blue screen\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/experience/performance-optimization/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR · Use Windows Update to receive the latest updates and drivers · Manually update drivers · Use System Restore or Startup Repair.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Gaming-Notebooks/error-on-startup-whea-uncorrectable-error-system-restarts/td-p/7339484\",\n      \"title\": \"error on startup whea_uncorrectable_error system restarts t...\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Dec 13, 2019 — Turn on the computer and immediately press Esc repeatedly, about once every second. When the menu appears, press the F2 key. On the main menu,\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.justanswer.com/computer/n9ji5-stop-code-whea-uncorrectable-error-laptop-may.html\",\n      \"title\": \"Stop code: WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR. My laptop. It may have been a while. I don't believe so. I don't think so...not\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"By chatting and providing personal info, you understand and agree to our [Terms of Service](https://www.justanswer.com/info/terms-of-service) and [Privacy Policy](https://www.justanswer.com/info/privacy-security) .\\n\\n[logo](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n\\nComputer\\n\\n[Home](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n\\nHow it Works\\n\\n[Contact us](https://www.justanswer.com/help/)\\n\\nHow it Works\\n\\nlogo\\n\\nJustAnswer expert consultation platform logo\\n\\nClose navigation menu button\\n\\nExplore All Categories\\n\\n[Home](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n\\n[Contact us](https://www.justanswer.com/help/)\\n\\n[Home](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n\\n[Contact us](https://www.justanswer.com/help/)\\n\\n1. [Ask an Expert](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n2. \\n3. [Ask a Computer Technician](https://www.justanswer.com/computer/)\\n\\nFound 2 result(s) for your search\\n\\n# Stop code: WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR on my HP 17 laptop running Windows 10, update failed, should I change my password?\\n\\nTechnician's Assistant chat Collapse expert chat details\\n**Customer:** Stop code: WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR\\n\\n**Technician's Assistant:** Just to clarify, which device is displaying the error code or message?\\n\\n**Customer:** My laptop.\\n\\n**Technician's Assistant:** When was the last time you changed the password for your laptop?\\n\\n**Customer:** It may have been a while.\\n\\n**Technician's Assistant:** Have you attempted to use a password reset disk or any recovery utility?\\n\\n**Customer:** No, I don't believe so.\\n\\n**Technician's Assistant:** Is there anything else the Computer Expert should know before I connect you? Rest assured that they will be able to assist you.\\n\\n**Customer:** I don't think so... I'm not sure, as I've never encountered this before.\\n\\nAnswered by Yasir Ansari in 5 mins 2 years ago\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Yasir Ansari\\n\\nExpert\\n\\nYasir Ansari customer rating\\n\\n**5,421** satisfied customers\\nSpecialities include: Computer, Computer Hardware, Email, Financial Software, Laptop, Microsoft Office, Networking, Software\\n\\nRead more\\n\\nWelcome! What's going on with your laptop?\\n\\nNew!\\n\\nWHEA uncorrectable error message\\n\\nLaptop won't boot properly\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nHello and good day! I’d like to welcome you to JustAnswer.com, an independent, paid Q&A site where you can get answers, information, and suggestions regarding any problem you may be facing.\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nHi, it's a pleasure to connect. How are you today?\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nI understand that you're experiencing an issue with your computer. Could you please tell me which Windows Edition you are using? Is it Windows 10 or Windows 11?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nWindow 10\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nExplore related questions\\n\\nDiscover more answers\\n\\nMy computer has been jammed for two and a half hours. Message read Stop Code WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR. Just now my\\n\\nI have windows crashing the error is WHEA. Windows 10 my computer was custom built. I have tried updating drivers but\\n\\nWindos on my laptop needs to be restarted. I have been asked to call and provide you with this: Stop code: WHEA\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nNo\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nDo you see the Advanced Options for repair on the screen?\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nDo you see **Advanced Options** on the blue screen?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nIs this the place where I need to pay $39?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nNo advance option on the blue screen.\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nI believe that's the automated message for remote assistance. Remote assistance won't work since your computer is in recovery mode.\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nCould you provide the make and model of your computer?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nWhat does that mean, and how long will it take?\\n\\nYasir Ansari - Expert profile photo\\n\\nSecure connection icon Tech Support Specialist: Yasir Ansari\\n\\nI apologize; I understand that your computer is experiencing a blue screen error. We need to boot the computer in recovery mode since you are unable to log in. To start in recovery mode, do you see the Advanced Repair options on the screen? If not, please press and hold the power button for 10 seconds to shut down the computer. Wait for a minute, then turn the computer back on.\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nIt's an HP 17 model, but I'm not certain where to find additional details about it.\\n\\n...\\n\\nunlike\\n\\n0 Likes\\n\\nShare: Share on Facebook social media platform Share on Twitter social media platform Share on LinkedIn professional network\\n\\nDisclaimer: The customer and expert messages presented herein may have been altered or modified to enhance readability and safeguard \"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.justanswer.com/laptop/di51k-laptop-keeps-getting-whea-uncorrectable-error-keeps.html\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Fix WHEA Uncorrectable Error on Your Laptop | Expert Q&A\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2020-02-02\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"justanswer.com/help/)\\n\\n[Home](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n\\n[Contact us](https://www.justanswer.com/help/)\\n\\n1. [Ask an Expert](https://www.justanswer.com)\\n2. \\n3. [Ask a Computer Technician](https://www.justanswer.com/computer/)\\n4. \\n5. [Laptop Questions](https://www.justanswer.com/laptop/)\\n\\nFound 2 result(s) for your search\\n\\n# My laptop keeps getting 'WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR' and keeps restarting - how do I fix this?\\n\\nTechnician's Assistant chat\\n\\n**Customer:**\\n\\nI'm experiencing a recurring issue with my laptop where it displays a 'WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR' and then restarts. What steps can I take to resolve this problem?\\n\\nAnswered by Hriday Dhali in 1 min6 years ago\\n\\nHriday Dhali\\n\\nNetwork Architect at TCS\\n\\n**4,483** satisfied customers\\n\\nSpecialities include: Computer, Computer Hardware, Email, Financial Software, Laptop, Mac, Microsoft Office, Networking, Printers, Programming\\n\\nRead more\\n\\nWelcome! How can I help with your {0} question?\\n\\nNew!\\n\\nHP laptop keeps restarting\\nHP laptop hardware diagnostics missing\\n\\nLaptop technician: Hriday Dhali\\n\\nHello! Welcome to JustAnswer. I am happy to assist you today.  \\nI am sorry to hear that you are experiencing issues with your computer. Hopefully, we can resolve this quickly.\\n\\nIs this the error code?\\n\\nCould you please provide the error code and the make and model of the laptop?\\n\\n?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\n‘WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR’ on my HP Pavilion Artist Edition  \\nmodel# \\\\*\\\\*\\\\*\\\\*\\\\* dv6-1260se\\n\\nLaptop technician: Hriday Dhali\\n\\nThank you. Please begin by running the hardware diagnostics to pinpoint the error.\\n\\nTurn on your PC, press Esc, and then F2 when prompted. Select System Tests (Fast Test conducts a 4-minute hardware check).\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nI don't see 'system test'... I see 'F1 system information', 'F2 startup test', 'F3 run-in test', and 'F4 hard disk test'.\\n\\nLaptop technician: Hriday Dhali\\n\\nF2\\n\\nDiscover more answers\\n\\nMy laptop keeps getting 'WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR' and keeps restarting - how do I fix this?\\n\\n...\\n\\nYou didn't respond to my question regarding why the primary hard disk self-test passed if there is an issue with the hard drive. Additionally, when I researched the 0301 error, it mentioned that other factors could be causing this, such as BIOS and other reasons. I'm on Social Security disability and don't have the extra funds to purchase a hard drive if that isn't the actual cause.\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nI won't provide a rating until the task is completed.\\n\\nLaptop technician: Hriday Dhali\\n\\nSure, how many hard disks are there?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nOnly the [1] main HDD\\n\\nLaptop technician: Hriday Dhali\\n\\nThe primary hard drive is corrupted, according to the results.\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\neven when the primary hard disk self-test passed, is the hard drive still corrupted?\\n\\nCustomer\\n\\nWhen I researched the 0301 error, I found that it could be caused by other factors, such as the BIOS and various other reasons.\\nI'm on Social Security disability and don't have the extra funds to purchase a hard drive if that's not the actual cause.\\n\\nRead less\\n\\n0 Likes\\n\\nShare:\\n\\nDisclaimer: The customer and expert messages presented herein may have been altered or modified to enhance readability and safeguard the privacy of individuals. These modifications do not change the intent or substance of the original messages.\\n\\nBack\\n\\nHriday Dhali\\n\\n4,483satisfied customers\\n\\nTech Support Specialist\\n\\nHriday Dhali\\n\\nTech Support Specialist\\n\\n4,483satisfied customers\\n\\nAsk your question here\\n\\n5 Tech Support Specialists are online right now.\\n\\nStart chat\\n\\n1\\n\\nMaximize\\n\\n## Dell XPS 15: Fixing WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR Crashes\\n\\n_XPS 15 often faces overheating and driver conflicts causing system instability and crashes._\\n\\nThe WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR indicates hardware issues like failing CPU, RAM, or overheating. Start by updating BIOS and all device drivers.\\nRun memory diagnostics to check RAM health and monitor CPU temperatures using software tools. Clean internal fans and vents to prevent overheating. If errors persist, test hardware components individually, focusing on the CPU and RAM. Reapplying thermal paste can improve cooling. Regular maintenance and driver updates help prevent this error and system restarts.\\n\\n**Disclaimer:** This information is AI-generated and intended for general guidance only. For advice specific to your situation, please consult a verified expert on JustAnswer before making decisions.\\n\\nHave a question? Ask now\\n\\nWelcome! How can I help with your {0} question?\\n\\nNew!\\n\\nHP laptop keeps restarting\\n\\nHP laptop hardware diagnostics missing\\n\\n#### Related Customer Questions\\n\\nView More\\n\\n#### Getting Started Is Easy\\n\\nAsk for help, 24/7\\n\\nAsk for help, 24/7\\n\\nMembers enjoy round-the-clock access to 12,000+ verified Experts, including doctors, lawyers, tech support, mechanics, vets, home repair pros, more.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://mdrepairs.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error\",\n      \"title\": \"WHEA Uncorrectable Error Fix | Windows Blue Screen\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-04-08\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"This is one of several blue screen errors that can indicate storage problems. The good news is that some causes are fixable with basic troubleshooting. Overheating, outdated drivers, bad BIOS settings. The bad news? If the error keeps coming back, you’re probably looking at a hardware failure. And if your storage drive is the culprit, your data could be at risk.\\n\\nWe see computers with this error come through our data recovery lab regularly. Sometimes it’s a simple overheating issue and the customer fixes it by cleaning out dust. Other times, the drive has bad sectors spreading across the platters, and recovery is the only way to save the files. The key is figuring out which situation you’re in before you lose anything important.\\n\\nIf you’re getting this blue screen repeatedly and you’re worried about your data, our data recovery team can evaluate your drive for free. No obligation, just answers.\\n\\n### What’s in This Guide\\n\\n* What Is the WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR?\\n* Common Causes of This Blue Screen\\n* Step-by-Step Fixes (Start Here)\\n* Advanced Fixes for Persistent Errors\\n* When WHEA Points to a Dying Drive\\n* Protecting Your Data During WHEA Errors\\n* When You Need Professional Data Recovery\\n* Frequently Asked Questions\\n\\n## What Is the WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR?\\n\\nWHEA is a system built into Windows (Vista and later) that monitors hardware components for errors. Your CPU, memory controller, PCIe bus, and storage controllers all report errors through WHEA. Most of the time, WHEA catches and corrects small errors silently in the background. You never even notice.\\n\\nThe blue screen happens when WHEA encounters an error it **cannot** correct. Something has gone wrong at the hardware level, and Windows decides the safest thing to do is stop everything immediately rather than risk data corruption or further damage. That’s what “uncorrectable” means. Windows tried to fix it, failed, and pulled the emergency brake.\\n\\nThe stop code is **0x00000124** .\\nYou’ll usually see it displayed on the blue screen itself, along with the text WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR. Windows 10 and 11 show a sad face emoji and the stop code. Older versions show the classic wall of white text on blue.\\n\\n**Quick context:** Not every blue screen means hardware failure. Driver crashes, software conflicts, and Windows Update bugs cause blue screens too. But WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR specifically indicates a _hardware_ error. That’s what makes it more serious than your average BSOD.\\n\\n### What Windows Is Actually Telling You\\n\\nWhen you get this BSOD, Windows creates a memory dump file with details about the error: which component failed, the error type, and sometimes a specific error code. Most people never look at these dumps. But tools like [WinDbg from Microsoft](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/debugger/) or the free BlueScreenView utility can parse them and tell you exactly which component flagged the error.\\n## Common Causes of This Blue Screen\\n\\nThe WHEA\\\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\\\_ERROR has several possible causes. Some are cheap fixes. Others mean a trip to the repair shop or data recovery lab. Let’s go through them in order from most common to least common.\\n\\n### Overheating (CPU or GPU)\\n\\nThis is the number one cause, and it’s usually the easiest to fix. Your CPU has built-in thermal protection. When it gets too hot, it starts throttling performance. If it gets dangerously hot (typically above 100C), it triggers a machine check exception, which WHEA catches and reports as uncorrectable.\\n\\nCommon overheating causes:\\n\\n* Dust buildup in fans and heatsinks\\n* Dried-out thermal paste (common on laptops older than 3-4 years)\\n* Failed or dying CPU fan\\n* Blocked air vents (laptops on soft surfaces like beds or couches)\\n* Overclocked CPU without adequate cooling\\n\\n### Faulty or Failing RAM\\n\\nBad memory sticks are the second most common cause.\\n\\n...\\n\\nSamsung, Western Digital, and Intel all have their own NVMe drivers that are more stable.\\n\\n#### 5 Update BIOS/UEFI Firmware\\n\\nMotherboard manufacturers regularly release BIOS updates that fix hardware compatibility issues. Check your motherboard manufacturer’s support page for the latest BIOS version. Follow their instructions carefully. A failed BIOS update can brick your motherboard, so don’t skip any steps and don’t lose power during the process.\\n\\n**Note:** On laptops, check the manufacturer’s support page (Dell, HP, Lenovo, ASUS, etc.) for both BIOS and firmware updates specific to your model.\\n\\n#### 6 Check Your Hard Drive or SSD Health\\n\\nOpen Command Prompt as Administrator and run:\\n\\n`wmic diskdrive get status`\\n\\nIf it says anything other than “OK,” your drive has reported a problem. For more detail, download [CrystalDiskInfo](https://crystalmark.info/en/software/crystaldiskinfo/) (free). It reads the SMART data from your drive and gives you a health status. Look for:\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Operating-System-and-Recovery/Blue-screen-error-stop-code-WHEA-UNCORRECTABLE-ERROR/td-p/9115716\",\n      \"title\": \"Blue screen error stop code : WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-07-07\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"* HP Pavilion Gaming 15-ec1000 Laptop PC (9EK33AV)\\n\\nView All (1)\\n\\nCategory:\\n\\n* Others\\n\\n[I have the same question](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.externalratingdisplay.ratingenumerationdisplay.link:rating/rating-enum/0/rating-system/forum_topic_metoo/message-uid/9115716?t:ac=board-id/OS/thread-id/662980&t:cp=ratings/contributionpage&ticket=r7TbP0rY_dPL_-1)\\n\\n1 ACCEPTED SOLUTION\\n\\nAccepted Solutions\\n\\nNal_NR\\n\\nModerator [Nal\\\\_NR](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/4700901)\\n\\n25,525 1,344 1,174 8,386\\n\\nModerator\\n\\n‎07-09-2024 07:46 AM\\n\\nHP Recommended\\n\\n* Mark as New\\n* Bookmark\\n* Subscribe\\n* \\n* Permalink\\n* Print\\n* \\n* Flag Post\\n\\nHi @AS773 ,\\n\\nWelcome to the HP Support Community.\\n\\nI'd be happy to help you!\\n\\nThe \\\"WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR\\\" is typically associated with hardware issues.\\n\\n...\\n\\nKeep me posted for further assistance\\n\\nPlease mark this post as “ **Accepted Solution** ” if the issue is resolved and if you feel this reply was helpful click “ **Yes** ”.\\n\\n**Nal\\\\_NR-  \\nHP Community Moderator  \\n**\\n\\nView solution in original post\\n\\nTags (1)\\n\\n* Tags:\\n* HP Pavilion Gaming 15-ec1000 Laptop PC (9EK33AV)\\n\\nView All (1)\\n\\nWas this reply helpful? [Yes](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.externalratingdisplay.ratingenumerationdisplay.link:rating/rating-enum/1/rating-system/medaltesttest/message-uid/9117708?t:ac=board-id/OS/thread-id/662980&t:cp=ratings/contributionpage&ticket=r7TbP0rY_dPL_-1) [No](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.externalratingdisplay.ratingenumerationdisplay.link:rating/rating-enum/0/rating-system/medaltesttest/message-uid/9117708?t:ac=board-id/OS/thread-id/662980&t:cp=ratings/contributionpage&ticket=r7TbP0rY_dPL_-1)\\n\\n3 REPLIES 3\\n\\nNal_NR\\n\\nModerator [Nal\\\\_NR](https://h30434.www3.hp.\\ncom/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/4700901)\\n\\n25,525 1,344 1,174 8,387\\n\\nModerator\\n\\n‎07-09-2024 07:46 AM\\n\\nHP Recommended\\n\\n* Mark as New\\n* Bookmark\\n* Subscribe\\n* \\n* Permalink\\n* Print\\n* \\n* Flag Post\\n\\nHi @AS773 ,\\n\\nWelcome to the HP Support Community.\\n\\nI'd be happy to help you!\\n\\nThe \\\"WHEA UNCORRECTABLE ERROR\\\" is typically associated with hardware issues. Since you've already tried updating the BIOS, formatting the C drive, and checking for bad sectors, there are a few other steps you can take to troubleshoot and potentially resolve the issue:\\n\\n**Check for Driver Issues** :\\n\\n* Ensure all your device drivers are up to date, especially for critical components like your GPU, CPU, and chipset.\\n\\n**Run Windows Memory Diagnostic** :\\n\\n* Press Win + R, type mdsched.exe, and press Enter.\\n* Choose \\\"Restart now and check for problems.\\\"\\n\\n**Check Event Viewer Logs** :\\n\\n* Press Win + X and select Event Viewer.\\n* Navigate to Windows Logs > System and look for critical errors around the time of the BSOD.\\n**Stress Test Your Hardware** :\\n\\n* Use tools like Prime95 to stress test your CPU and MemTest86 for RAM.\\n\\n**Update Firmware/Drivers** :\\n\\n* Visit the HP support website and ensure all firmware and drivers for your specific model (HP Pavilion Gaming 15-Ec1000) are up to date.\\n\\n**Disable Overclocking** :\\n\\n* If you have any overclocking settings enabled in the BIOS or through software, disable them and see if the issue persists.\\n\\n**Check for Overheating** :\\n\\n* Use software like HWMonitor to check the temperatures of your CPU and GPU to ensure they are not overheating.\\n\\n**Reseat Hardware Components** :\\n\\n* If comfortable, try reseating your RAM, SSD/HDD, and other removable components to ensure they are properly connected.\\n\\n**Run System File Checker (SFC) and DISM** :\\n\\n* Open Command Prompt as an administrator.\\n* Run sfc /scannow and wait for it to complete.\\n* Then run DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth.\\n\\n**Check PSU and Battery** :\\n* Ensure that your laptop’s power supply unit (PSU) and battery are functioning correctly and providing stable power.\\n\\n**Windows Update** :\\n\\n* Ensure your Windows operating system is fully updated.\\n\\nIf none of these steps resolve the issue, it might be a deeper hardware fault. I recommend you contact phone support.\\n\\nHope this helps! Keep me posted for further assistance\\n\\nPlease mark this post as “ **Accepted Solution** ” if the issue is resolved and if you feel this reply was helpful click “ **Yes** ”.\\n\\n**Nal\\\\_NR-  \\nHP Community Moderator  \\n**\\n\\nTags (1)\\n\\n* Tags:\\n* HP Pavilion Gaming 15-ec1000 Laptop PC (9EK33AV)\\n\\nView All (1)\\n\\nWas this reply helpful? [Yes](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.externalratingdisplay.ratingenumerationdisplay.link:rating/rating-enum/1/rating-system/medaltesttest/message-uid/9117708?t:ac=board-id/OS/thread-id/662980&t:cp=ratings/contributionpage&ticket=r7TbP0rY_dPL_-1) [No](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZLCibJgtGcA\",\n      \"title\": \"HP Laptop - How to Fix 0x0000012B Blue Screen Error Code ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-04-01\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Fixing the Blue Screen of Death (BSOD) Error on Windows 10: A Step-by-Step Guide Very important: Follow this video, even if you see any error in any command, you move to the next command.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://github.com/iammhador/hp-omen-linux-shutdown-fix/blob/main/README.md\",\n      \"title\": \"hp-omen-linux-shutdown-fix/README.md at main · iammhador/hp-omen-linux-shutdown-fix · GitHub\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"> **Device:** HP OMEN 16 (also applicable to Lenovo, ASUS Gaming series with similar ACPI issues) **Boot Manager:** rEFInd **Linux Distro:** Fedora (applies to any Linux distro on this hardware)\\n> \\n> \\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## 📋 Table of Contents\\n\\n* The Problem\\n* Root Cause\\n* The Solution\\n* How It Works\\n* Prerequisites\\n* Implementation\\n  \\n    + Phase 1: Windows Side\\n    + Phase 2: Linux Side\\n* Full Flow Diagram\\n* rEFInd Auto-Restore Service\\n* Hide GRUB Menu\\n* Troubleshooting\\n* Reverting Everything\\n* Why efibootmgr Doesn't Work\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## The Problem\\n\\nOn HP OMEN 16 (and similar gaming laptops), shutting down from Linux does not fully power off the hardware. Specifically:\\n\\n* The shutdown animation completes and the screen goes dark\\n* But the **GPU, fans, and background processes keep running**\\n* The system stays in a half-on state, generating heat silently\\n* This is because Linux triggers **ACPI S3** (suspend) instead of **ACPI S5** (full power off)\\n* Windows shuts down cleanly (S5 works fine from Windows)\\n* This affects **all Linux distributions** on this hardware — not just Fedora\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Root Cause\\n\\nHP OMEN's firmware has a known ACPI implementation issue where the `shutdown` syscall from Linux does not correctly trigger the S5 power state. This is a hardware/firmware-level problem that cannot be fixed from Linux alone.\\n\\nAdditionally, HP OMEN (and many gaming laptops from HP, Lenovo, ASUS) have **firmware-level EFI boot entry protection** , which means:\\n\\n* Tools like `efibootmgr` cannot reliably create persistent boot entries\\n* `BootNext` EFI variable is often ignored or cleared by the firmware\\n* Any \\\"unknown\\\" EFI entries get deleted on every boot\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## The Solution\\n\\nSince Windows shuts down cleanly (S5), we route the shutdown **through Windows** :\\n\\n1. A **special key** (the AI button / `KEY_PROG2` ) is bound to a script\\n2. The script modifies `refind.conf` to instantly boot Windows and creates a **flag file** on the EFI partition\\n3.\\nOn Windows startup, a **SYSTEM-level task** checks for the flag file\\n4. If flag exists → restore `refind.conf` \\\\+ delete flag + shut down cleanly\\n5. If no flag → do nothing (normal Windows use is unaffected)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## How It Works\\n\\n```\\n[Special Key Pressed from Fedora]\\n          ↓\\nLinux script runs:\\n  - Modifies refind.conf → timeout -1, default_selection \\\"Windows\\\"\\n  - Creates flag file at /boot/efi/EFI/refind/shutdown_flag\\n  - Reboots system\\n          ↓\\nrEFInd reads modified config → instantly boots Windows (no menu shown)\\n          ↓\\nWindows boots → SYSTEM task runs at startup (before login screen)\\n          ↓\\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n    │  Flag file exists?              │\\n    │  YES → Delete flag              │\\n    │      → Restore refind.conf      │\\n    │        (timeout 10, Fedora)     │\\n    │      → Shutdown /s /t 5         │\\n\\n...\\n\\nservice\\n\\n #  Remove rEFInd protect service \\nsudo systemctl disable refind-protect.service 2> /dev/null\\nsudo rm -f /usr/local/bin/refind-protect.sh\\nsudo rm -f /etc/systemd/system/refind-protect.service\\n\\nsudo systemctl daemon-reload\\n\\n #  Remove GNOME key binding \\ngsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys custom-keybindings \\\" [] \\\" \\n\\n #  Restore refind.conf \\nsudo sed -i ' s/^timeout .*/timeout 10/ ' /boot/efi/EFI/Microsoft/Boot/refind.conf\\nsudo sed -i ' s/^default_selection .*/default_selection \\\"Fedora\\\"/ ' /boot/efi/EFI/Microsoft/Boot/refind.conf\\n\\n #  Remove flag file if exists \\nsudo rm -f /boot/efi/EFI/refind/shutdown_flag\\n```\\n\\nOn Windows side:\\n\\n1. Open `taskschd.msc`\\n2. Find and delete **\\\"Linux Shutdown Task\\\"**\\n3. Delete `C:\\\\shutdown_check.bat`\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Why efibootmgr Doesn't Work\\n\\nYou might think the simpler solution is `efibootmgr --bootnext` to boot Windows directly. This **does not work** on HP OMEN and many gaming laptops because:\\n* HP firmware **deletes unknown EFI boot entries** on every boot\\n* The `BootNext` EFI variable is **ignored or cleared** by HP's firmware\\n* This is a known issue with HP, Lenovo, and ASUS gaming series laptops\\n* The firmware enforces its own boot order and doesn't respect OS-level EFI variable writes reliably\\n\\nThe `refind.conf` \\\\+ flag file approach works because it operates entirely at the **filesystem level** (FAT32 EFI partition) which the firmware cannot interfere with.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Hardware Info\\n\\n|Item |Detail |\\n| --- | --- |\\n|Device |HP OMEN 16 |\\n|Boot Manager |rEFInd |\\n|Linux |Fedora (any distro applies) |\\n|Special Key |AI Button ( `KEY_PROG2` , keycode 149, X11: `XF86Launch2` ) |\\n|EFI Partition |`/dev/nvme0n1p4` mounted at `/boot/efi` |\\n|rEFInd Config |`/boot/efi/EFI/Microsoft/Boot/refind.conf` |\\n|Flag File |`/boot/efi/EFI/refind/shutdown_flag` |\\n|Windows Script |`C:\\\\shutdown_check.bat` |\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Credits\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Notebook-Software-and-How-To-Questions/Fix-OmenCommandCenterbackground-exe-Leak/td-p/9436369\",\n      \"title\": \"Fix OmenCommandCenterbackground.exe Leak - HP Support ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Fix OmenCommandCenterbackground.exe Leak - HP Support ...\\nMy HP Envy x360 Laptop has a memory leak from OmenCommandCenterbackground.exe, which I understand can slow the PC down. How is it fixed?\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0d4353dd7ffeoTARvc1WgAxYSp\"\n}",
