      "text": "Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me compile the complete Root Cause Analysis.\n\n**CONFIRMED BSOD HISTORY (from WER-SystemErrorReporting):**\n\n| Date | Stop Code | Parameters | Dump Location |\n|------|-----------|------------|---------------|\n| 12/05/2026 | **0x0000012b** (WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR) | 0xffffffffc00002c4, 0x00000000000001e5, 0x000001402f3bcdf0, 0xffffab006543b000 | C:\\WINDOWS\\MEMORY.DMP |\n| 15/05/2026 | **0x000000be** (ATTEMPTED_WRITE_TO_READONLY_MEMORY) | 0xfffff1f9f9fff9e8, 0x8a00000000200021, 0xfffff582ab6b1c80, 0x000000000000000a | C:\\WINDOWS\\MEMORY.DMP |\n| 17/06/2026 | **0x000000be** (ATTEMPTED_WRITE_TO_READONLY_MEMORY) | 0xfffff24b4dfd4b48, 0x8a00000000200021, 0xfffff58fcc4b1b10, 0x000000000000000a | C:\\WINDOWS\\MEMORY.DMP |\n| 20/06/2026 | **0x0000012b** (WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR) | 0xffffffffc00002c4, 0x00000000000004fc, 0x000002be843b5c00, 0xffff95818607a000 | C:\\WINDOWS\\MEMORY.DMP |\n| ~03/07/2026 | Unknown (BSOD photo from user) | WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR | Dump creation FAILED |\n\nSo there are at least 4 confirmed BSODs in logs, plus the ones the user experienced yesterday.\n\n**KEY OBSERVATION about parameters:**\n- Both WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR have the first parameter **0xffffffffc00002c4** - this is STATUS_HARDWARE_INTERFACE_ERROR, which specifically points to a hardware interface error\n- Both ATTEMPTED_WRITE_TO_READONLY_MEMORY have the second parameter **0x8a00000000200021** - this indicates a kernel-mode driver attempted to write to read-only memory\n\n**ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS SUMMARY:**\n\nThe most likely root causes, in order of probability:\n\n1. **Memory (RAM) issues** - 80% confidence\n   - Mixed RAM modules (SK Hynix + Samsung)\n   - Multiple BSODs including WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR and ATTEMPTED_WRITE_TO_READONLY_MEMORY\n   - The 0x000000be (ATTEMPTED_WRITE_TO_READONLY_MEMORY) can indicate faulty RAM\n   - Consistent virtual memory exhaustion exacerbates the problem\n\n2. **Overheating / Thermal issues** - 60% confidence\n   - HP OMEN gaming laptop (known for thermal issues)\n   - i5-7300HQ is a 45W TDP CPU in a laptop chassis\n   - Dried thermal paste likely on a ~9 year old laptop\n   - No thermal data available through WMI (sensors may not be accessible)\n   - WHEA errors can be triggered by thermal protection\n\n3. **Failing storage / disk issues** - 40% confidence\n   - HGST HDD (7200RPM, mechanical) is old and could be developing bad sectors\n   - Volsnap errors suggest disk I/O issues\n   - Dump file creation failures (volmgr 161) could indicate disk write issues\n\n4. **Outdated/Incompatible drivers** - 50% confidence\n   - NVIDIA driver from April 2023 (over 3 years old!)\n   - XTU3SERVICE (Intel XTU) failing to start - could indicate overclocking software issues\n   - Various driver-related DCOM errors\n\n5. **Paging file misconfiguration** - 70% confidence (contributing factor)\n   - Page file fixed at 12GB for 16GB system\n   - Multiple \"paging file too small\" errors\n   - Memory exhaustion from chrome + vmmem (WSL2) consistently\n\n6. **Firmware/BIOS issues** - 30% confidence\n   - TPM-WMI errors about Secure Boot keys\n   - Old firmware version   - HP OMEN known ACPI issues\n\nNow let me present the iFixit-style fixability score. Since there's no actual \"iFix\" tool, I'll create an enterprise-grade fixability assessment based on the iFixit repairability scoring methodology adapted for software issues.",
